                    <div class="row">
                    <img src="assets/close.png" title="Close" style="height: 10px; width: auto; cursor: pointer;" onclick="closeArticle('#col-num-3');">
                        <div class="row list" id="metaview-3"><h3>Metaviewer</h3>
                        <ul id="metadata-list-3"></ul></div> 

                    </div> 
                    <div class="card overflow" id="article-3">


	<meta charset="utf-8">
	<title>What we learned about wellness while working from home, and how to use those insights</title>


	<figure>
		<img src="assets/offices.webp">
		<figcaption>Whether workers wind up at home, in offices or in hybrid work systems, mental health experts hope bosses‚Äô decisions will prioritize individual well-being as much as possible. (iStock)
</figcaption>
	</figure>
	<h1>What we learned about wellness while working from home, and how to use those insights</h1>
 	<h3 class="auth">By <a href="https://www.washingtonpost.com/people/allyson-chiu/">Allyson Chiu</a></h3>
 	<h3 class="pub">June 25, 2021</h3>
 	<p>Before the <a href="https://www.washingtonpost.com/coronavirus/?itid=lk_inline_manual_1">coronavirus</a> <span class="event pandemic">pandemic</span>, psychiatrist <span class="person gold" id="person-86"> Jessi Gold</span> could count on one hand the number of times she had conducted an appointment over the phone or computer.</p>

	<p>‚ÄúWhen we switched to being home in March, it was like, <span class="quote" id="quote-53">‚ÄòOkay, it‚Äôs a short-term thing. I can do this short term,‚Äô‚Äâ‚Äù</span> said<span class="person gold" id="person-87">Gold</span>, 33, who sees health-care workers and college students at <span class="institution wusmsl" id="institution-62">Washington University School of Medicine in St. Louis</span>. But as weeks stretched into months,<span class="person gold" id="person-88">Gold</span>, a self-described extrovert, began to feel the strain.</p>

	<p><span class="quote" id="quote-54">‚ÄúI would burn out a lot easier just staring at the computer all day. I got headaches a lot quicker. I would feel myself needing to get up and walk around and make myself have breaks,‚Äù</span> she said.<span class="person gold" id="person-89">Gold</span> also found herself missing her connection with patients, even though she was seeing them virtually.</p>

	<p>When<span class="person gold" id="person-90">Gold</span> returned to in-person sessions once a week last month, <span class="quote" id="quote-55">‚Äúit was like night and day for me,‚Äù she said. ‚ÄúI was much happier. I left work feeling so much better.‚Äù</span></p>

	<p><a href="https://hosted-washpost.submissionplatform.com/sub/hosted/6082eb55360c930024d30657"><i>Tell us about the hardest parts of life after social distancing</i></a></p>

	<p><span class="person swamy" id="person-91">Lakshman Swamy</span>, on the other hand, is in no rush to return to his traditional office setting. <span class="quote" id="quote-56">‚ÄúAlthough I feel like I‚Äôm working a lot .‚Äâ.‚Äâ. the comfort of doing that work is really increased,‚Äù</span> said <span class="person swamy" id="person-92">Swamy</span>, 38, medical director at <span class="institution masshealth" id="institution-63">Masshealth</span> and an ICU doctor in <span class="place boston" id="place-31">Boston</span>, whose current schedule allows him to alternate three-week stretches of remote work with one week at the hospital.</p>

	<p>
	<span class="person swamy" id="person-93">Swamy</span> said he is more productive at home, largely because he doesn‚Äôt have to commute and has a ‚Äúpreserved workspace.‚Äù In addition, he said, working remotely has allowed him to spend more time with his family and take better care of himself ‚Äî attending meetings while walking, for example, and making more nutritious meals. <span class="quote" id="quote-57">‚ÄúI can bake fresh bread and eat it for breakfast while I‚Äôm in a meeting,‚Äù he said. ‚ÄúIt‚Äôs amazing.‚Äù</span></p>

	<p><a href="https://www.washingtonpost.com/business/2020/10/14/top-workplaces-2020-working-from-home/?itid=lk_interstitial_manual_11"><i>At work while at home: The new paradigm</i></a></p>

	<p>Across the country, office workers and professionals like<span class="person gold" id="person-94">Gold</span> and <span class="person swamy" id="person-95">Swamy</span> have experienced the pros and cons of working from home, and are considering which elements they would like to incorporate or scrap in their post-<span class="event pandemic">pandemic</span> work lives. Mental health experts are hoping that decisions made by employers will prioritize individual well-being as much as possible.</p>

	<p><span class="quote" id="quote-58">‚ÄúBefore we had these cookie-cutter expectations of working processes,‚Äù</span> said <span class="person barber" id="person-96">Lacie Barber</span>, an associate professor of psychology at <span class="institution sdsu" id="institution-64">San Diego State University</span>, who specializes in occupational health psychology. <span class="quote" id="quote-59">‚ÄúThe benefit of covid is it made us change everything.‚Äù Rather than ‚Äúrushing to go back to the way things were,‚Äù <span class="person barber" id="person-97">Barber</span> said, organizations should ‚Äúactually think about how it could be better than where we were.‚Äù</span></p>

	<p>	And while much of the country‚Äôs workers ‚Äî front-line and essential employees or those in the service industry ‚Äî don‚Äôt have the option of doing their jobs remotely (according to a May survey <a href="https://www.bls.gov/cps/effects-of-the-coronavirus-covid-19-htm">conducted by the <span class="institution usbls" id="institution-65">U.S. Bureau of Labor Statistics</span></a>, only 17 percent of employed people 16 and older said they had teleworked in the past four weeks), experts say wisdom gained during the <span class="event pandemic">pandemic</span> can be beneficial in any work environment.</p>

	<p><span class="quote" id="quote-60">‚ÄúEmployers are increasingly recognizing the importance of stress management, of setting healthy boundaries, <a href="https://workplacementalhealth.org/Employer-Resources/Working-Remotely-During-COVID-19">of taking care of mental health and well-being</a>,‚Äù</span> said <span class="person gruttadaro" id="person-98">Darcy Gruttadaro</span>, director of the <span class="institution cwmh" id="institution-66">Center for Workplace Mental Health</span> at the <span class="institution apa" id="institution-67">American Psychiatric Association</span>.</p>

	<p><a href="https://www.washingtonpost.com/lifestyle/wellness/work-mental-health-day-naomi-osaka/2021/06/03/471847ae-c3cc-11eb-93f5-ee9558eecf4b_story.html?itid=lk_interstitial_manual_18"><i>How to know when you need a mental health break and ways to make the most of it</i></a></p>

	<p>Going forward, experts would like to see bosses create <span class="quote" id="quote-61">‚Äúsafe avenues for our employees and our team members to be comfortable and confident in disclosing what their needs are and what their mental health challenges are,‚Äù</span> said  <span class="person boatwright" id="person-99">Julius Boatwright</span>, founder and chief executive of <a href="https://www.steelsmilingpgh.org/">Steel Smiling</a>, a <span class="place pittsburgh" id="place-32">Pittsburgh</span>-based nonprofit organization that focuses on Black mental health.</p>

	<p>	And they would like to see all employees ‚Äî even those who don‚Äôt have a choice about where they work ‚Äî advocate for an environment that <span class="quote" id="quote-62">‚Äúyou believe is better for you, your job and your overall mental health,‚Äù</span> said <span class="person benjamin-miller" id="person-100">Benjamin Miller</span>, a mental health expert and president for <a href="https://wellbeingtrust.org/"><span class="insitution wbt">Well Being Trust</span></a>, a national foundation.</p>

	<p>Here are some lessons learned while working from home that experts say bosses and employees should keep in mind ‚Äî whether work stays remote, returns to an office or becomes a hybrid model.</p>

	<p><a href="https://subscribe.washingtonpost.com/newsletters/#/bundle/abetterweek?method=SURL&amp;location=ART&amp;itid=lk_interstitial_manual_24"><i>Find time you didn‚Äôt know you had with A Better Week, a 7-day email course</i></a></p>

	<h4>It can improve well-being</h4>
	<p>How a person‚Äôs well-being was affected by working from home was largely ‚Äúgrounded by privilege‚Äù related to job responsibilities, home life, neighborhood and socioeconomic status, among other factors, <span class="person benjamin-miller" id="person-101">Miller</span> said.</p>

	<p>But for some people, the <span class="event pandemic">pandemic</span> proved <span class="quote" id="quote-63">‚Äúthat we can integrate wellness into our lifestyle and still get work done,‚Äù</span> said <span class="person boatwright" id="person-102">Boatwright</span>, who has found time for healthy activities and encourages his staff to schedule at least an hour or two of self-care during the workweek.</p>

	<p>	Even if you have to return to the office, experts say, it‚Äôs possible to continue self-care. <span class="person boatwright" id="person-103">Boatwright</span> suggested incorporating simple breathing exercises, which don‚Äôt take more than three to five minutes, into your workday.</p>

	<p>Bosses can contribute to employees‚Äô well-being on-site by offering to hold walking meetings outdoors, inviting mindfulness experts to lead guided sessions for staff or sponsoring occasional healthy lunches, <span class="person gruttadaro" id="person-104">Gruttadaro</span> said.</p>

	<h4>It can interfere with boundaries</h4>
	<p>The past 15 months have shown that one of the main challenges of remote employment is the <span class="quote" id="quote-64">‚Äúblurring of boundaries‚Äù between work and home, <span class="person benjamin-miller" id="person-105">Miller</span> said. ‚ÄúAnd that leads to all kinds of problems.‚Äù</span></p>

	<p><a href="https://www.washingtonpost.com/lifestyle/wellness/burnout-prevent-recover-work-advice/2021/06/14/d897dc1a-cd4c-11eb-8014-2f3926ca24d9_story.html?itid=lk_interstitial_manual_34"><i>What burnout really means, and what bosses and employees can do about it</i></a></p>

	<p><span class="person gruttadaro" id="person-106">Gruttadaro</span> agreed. <span class="quote" id="quote-65">‚ÄúIf you used to work eight hours and now you‚Äôre working 10 to 11 hours, something else is being given up as part of your life,‚Äù she said. ‚ÄúIf it‚Äôs social connectedness, if it‚Äôs doing activities you previously loved, if it‚Äôs exercise, those are all unfortunate things to give up because that‚Äôs what keeps us healthy.‚Äù</span></p>

	<p>	The increased reliance on emails and other electronic communications while working remotely also can exacerbate <a href="https://psycnet.apa.org/record/2014-45450-001">‚Äúworkplace telepressure‚Äù</a> (feeling like you have to respond immediately to text-based messages), said <span class="person barber" id="person-107">Barber</span>, who has <a href="https://onlinelibrary.wiley.com/doi/abs/10.1002/smi.2864">researched</a> the subject. This in turn can lead to higher levels of work fatigue and sleep problems.</p>

	<p>With more people on flexible schedules, ‚Äúreestablishing predictability‚Äù at work is key to reducing telepressure, <span class="person barber" id="person-108">Barber</span> said. Leaders and subordinates should have discussions about explicit ground rules for communication, including expected response times, and bosses should reinforce those rules by not contacting employees outside those hours. Telling people to simply ignore messages sent at unusual times doesn‚Äôt work, she said.</p>

	<p><a href="https://hosted-washpost.submissionplatform.com/sub/hosted/60524dec02ab8605ab77641e"><i>Do you have questions about home improvement or homeownership?</i></a></p>

	<p>Bosses also can model healthy behavior for both at-home and office workers by encouraging employees to use vacation and take time off themselves, experts said. They should also regularly check in on staff, wherever they are.</p>

	<p>Advertisement
	For at-home employees, experts suggested learning to psychologically detach from their work. Possibilities include creating a <span class="quote" id="quote-66">‚Äú<a href="https://www.washingtonpost.com/lifestyle/wellness/fake-commute-home-work-transition-/2021/02/22/49f79d56-6cb7-11eb-9f80-3d7646ce1bc0_story.html?itid=lk_inline_manual_44">fake commute</a>,‚Äù taking a walk after work or even just closing the laptop. Such habits can send ‚Äúa signal that you‚Äôre done with work,‚Äù</span> <span class="person benjamin-miller" id="person-109">Miller</span> said.</p>

	<p><a href="https://www.washingtonpost.com/lifestyle/wellness/fake-commute-home-work-transition-/2021/02/22/49f79d56-6cb7-11eb-9f80-3d7646ce1bc0_story.html?itid=lk_interstitial_manual_45"><i>Why a fake commute could pave the way to work-from-home balance</i></a></p>

	<h4>It can allow more individualized schedules and settings</h4>
	<p>While there is a heightened risk of blurred boundaries in remote work, many workers appreciate having more control over when and how they work, <span class="person gruttadaro" id="person-110">Gruttadaro</span> said. Some people have adapted their schedules to suit their natural energy levels; perhaps they feel most productive early in the morning or they may be night owls. Others enjoy being able to <a href="https://www.washingtonpost.com/lifestyle/wellness/nap-pandemic-home-how-sleep/2021/01/29/d2cc6cbe-6015-11eb-9430-e7c77b5b0297_story.html?itid=lk_inline_manual_47">squeeze in a nap</a> in the early afternoon and benefit from a boost in productivity afterward. These advantages can be difficult to replicate in a traditional office setting.</p>

	<p><a href="https://www.washingtonpost.com/lifestyle/wellness/nap-pandemic-home-how-sleep/2021/01/29/d2cc6cbe-6015-11eb-9430-e7c77b5b0297_story.html?itid=lk_interstitial_manual_48"><i>Nap time is the new coffee break. Here‚Äôs how to make the most of it.</i></a></p>

	<p>There are some employees, however, who might need a more structured schedule and setting to motivate themselves, and for them, returning to an office environment may be beneficial, experts said.</p>


	<p>Personality type matters, too. Introverts may thrive in the quiet and solitude they have at home; extroverts may do better working face-to-face with colleagues.</p>

	<p>Working from home has been a mixed bag for many parents, who enjoyed spending more time with their children but experienced increased stress and strain from juggling work, child care and school. Many of them might have longed for office life during the <span class="event pandemic">pandemic</span>, <span class="person benjamin-miller" id="person-111">Miller</span> said, but when children go back to in-person learning, home offices might become more appealing.</p>

	<p>Experts emphasized that the constantly shifting work landscape reinforces the importance of having open and honest conversations about work expectations.</p>

	<p><a href="https://www.washingtonpost.com/lifestyle/2021/01/25/work-from-home-parenting-distractions/?itid=lk_interstitial_manual_55"><i>6 strategies for parents struggling with work-from-home interruptions</i></a></p>

	<h4>It can challenge social connections</h4>
	<p>Losing in-person contact with co-workers, family and friends during the <span class="event pandemic">pandemic</span> <span class="quote" id="quote-67">‚Äúwas a very unnatural thing to happen and that stressed a lot of people out,‚Äù</span> leading to increased rates of isolation and loneliness, <span class="person gruttadaro" id="person-112">Gruttadaro</span> said.</p>

	<p>It‚Äôs difficult to develop and maintain relationships while fully online, <span class="person barber" id="person-113">Barber</span> said. In offices, there are more opportunities for informal interactions with colleagues or bosses throughout the day <span class="quote" id="quote-68">‚Äúthat really do build up those relationships.‚Äù</span></p>

	<p><a href="https://www.washingtonpost.com/lifestyle/2021/03/03/stanford-zoom-fatigue/?itid=lk_interstitial_manual_61"><i>Four reasons you‚Äôre tired of <span class="insitution zoom">Zoom</span> calls ‚Äî and what to do about it</i></a></p>

	<p>While a return to an office setting or a hybrid work model may ease some of these pressures, there are also options for better maintaining social ties remotely. <span class="person barber" id="person-114">Barber</span> suggests, for example, that managers set aside time during virtual meetings for casual chit chat, rather than diving straight into work matters.</p>

	<p>‚Äú<span class="quote" id="quote-69">When it comes to the workplace, there is a difference between speaking to someone on a screen and seeing them in person‚Äù <span class="person gruttadaro" id="person-115">Gruttadaro</span> said. ‚ÄúThere is just this feeling of closeness that comes with being in the same room and there is more of a likelihood to, perhaps in some cases, share more personal information and just really have a more meaningful conversation.‚Äù</span></p>

	
	
